WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.680
We were having a story, when last seen, I was back from the emergency room the following

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:14.960
day and wondering what had happened to me.

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:20.840
And like all of you here, hopefully all of you here, I have the power of R and RStudio

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:22.840
and I know how to do an internet search.

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:27.320
So I found a blog post that told me how to export all the data from the Apple health

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:28.799
export.

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:30.400
And that's what I did.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:31.980
And I also know ggplot.

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:33.020
And I did this chart.

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:37.400
This is the very chart that I took with me to my doctor a couple days later.

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:39.959
It's not a very fancy chart.

00:00:39.959 --> 00:00:46.400
The vertical axis shows my pulse, the horizontal axis is the time of day, zero is midnight.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:55.400
And you can see about, there is the event that sent me to the emergency room, my perception

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:59.200
event that sent me to the emergency room.

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:03.599
In the middle of the night, about 1.30 a.m., this is when I was upset, got up, took some

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:07.400
bicarbonate of soda, the whole thing did not last very long, went back to bed, went to

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:08.400
sleep.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:12.279
While I was asleep, my pulse was going up gradually, which is very unusual.

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:15.080
And then hit that and off I went.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:20.800
And that's the story of my visit to the emergency room, which was not a big deal.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:26.199
But it does provide an example of how your health tracker is basically making a recording

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:28.519
of your life with data.

00:01:28.519 --> 00:01:34.680
So in order to do this chart and to look into this a little bit more, I had to sort of dig

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:37.959
into the Apple health export.

00:01:37.959 --> 00:01:43.279
And the first thing that sort of blew me away was just the sheer volume of data.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:51.400
Never in my professional life have I worked with a data set nearly as large as me.

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:54.040
And I was kind of excited about that and it was kind of fun.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:58.199
So 3.9 million rows, 1.2 million rows in the last year alone.

00:01:58.199 --> 00:02:03.080
I mean, as we speak, I am adding rows to the data.

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:10.520
And I also did some additional stuff to try to say, was this night unusual?

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:13.520
And went back and tried to look for other examples and didn't find anything, which was

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:14.839
a good thing.

00:02:14.839 --> 00:02:22.320
So I have all this incredible amount of data, but you think of it as a recording of your

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:26.199
life, but if you had an audio recording or a visual recording of your life, most of those

00:02:26.199 --> 00:02:28.199
moments wouldn't be very interesting.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:29.440
And the same is true of the data.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:33.399
There's a lot of data which is dull.

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:38.880
It's 70% of the data is this sort of low-level stuff, your heart rate, your active energy

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.960
as you're moving around and so on.

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:47.080
But there are a bunch of summary measures and other categories of measures.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:52.600
Basically, this is what you see on the health app on the iPhone, or you see sort of these

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:59.360
icons with these categories of things that it's keeping track of.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:04.919
And underneath each of those, or with each of those, are set of individual measures.

00:03:04.919 --> 00:03:07.839
And this is the measure, the ones that would fit on the screen.

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:09.960
There are quite a few more than this.

00:03:09.960 --> 00:03:14.199
And so you can get into any one of these things.

00:03:14.199 --> 00:03:18.160
Each of them has a sort of a story and may be relevant to different factors.

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:27.679
So you have heart rate, of course, but you have your stuff about sleep, which is not

00:03:27.679 --> 00:03:32.080
showing here, and step count and things like that.

00:03:32.080 --> 00:03:37.919
So let's talk about what is the Apple health export.

00:03:37.919 --> 00:03:43.479
So basically, on the iPhone, there is a database of all of this information.

00:03:43.479 --> 00:03:46.320
And that's what's sitting underneath the health app.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:54.679
And Apple, if you're an app developer on the iPhone, the API to that database is called

00:03:54.679 --> 00:03:56.119
the health kit.

00:03:56.119 --> 00:03:59.759
And what's happening is, is measurements are being fed in from the watch, are being fed

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:00.759
in from the phone.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:02.559
They're also coming in from other apps.

00:04:02.559 --> 00:04:07.479
For example, I have Lose It on my phone, which is a calorie counting app, which I have occasionally

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:08.479
used.

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:12.000
I have a blood pressure cuff, which has a Bluetooth connection to my phone.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.320
I also have it set up so it has a connection to my electronic health record, so it's all

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:19.519
of the records from my doctor.

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:24.519
All of that goes into this database, and it becomes accessible via the export.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:28.880
And when you actually ask for an export, in my case, it takes it about nine minutes before

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:30.799
it can assemble this whole thing.

00:04:30.799 --> 00:04:35.600
And then I can export it to my laptop and load it into R.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:43.839
Now, when I unzip this export file on my laptop, I think it's like three and a half gigabytes,

00:04:43.839 --> 00:04:45.760
which again is sort of crazy.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:47.399
It's a very wordy format.

00:04:47.399 --> 00:04:50.239
There's basically one table that I care about.

00:04:50.239 --> 00:04:57.880
And that one is, before I process it in, that one is like one and a half gigabytes.

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:01.839
So it is a tidy table, this table.

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:03.000
You don't even have to tidy it up.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:04.739
It's already a tidy table.

00:05:04.739 --> 00:05:11.880
It's got one row per measurement for my 3.9 measurements or whatever, 3.9 million, whatever

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:13.359
it was.

00:05:13.359 --> 00:05:19.640
And each row has a start time stamp, an end time stamp, the type of what is being measured,

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:25.019
the value, and the source of the measurement, the phone or my blood pressure cuff or whatever,

00:05:25.019 --> 00:05:29.579
and the version of the software that did that measurement.

00:05:29.579 --> 00:05:33.540
So you'll focus on type and value usually, but you'd need to pay attention to the source

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:35.059
and the version as well.

00:05:35.059 --> 00:05:39.540
The source, so for example, your step count is being produced by the watch, but the phone

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:41.339
is also producing a step count.

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:42.339
They both get fed in.

00:05:42.339 --> 00:05:45.940
If you don't pay attention to the source, you end up double counting, and I've had that

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:48.619
happen with other measures as well.

00:05:48.619 --> 00:05:52.179
So let's look at a measure.

00:05:52.179 --> 00:05:53.260
This is resting heart rate.

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:56.140
I'm interested in what's the trend in resting heart rate.

00:05:56.140 --> 00:06:01.100
We have on the vertical axis heart rate, on the horizontal axis, we have more than four

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:07.980
years worth of data here, one point per day, and all of this feels very personal to me.

00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:12.059
So I look at a chart like this, and I look at this thing, and I look at the smooth line

00:06:12.059 --> 00:06:15.899
that I put through this chart, and I say, whoa, what's going on here?

00:06:15.899 --> 00:06:18.339
Why is this line doing this?

00:06:18.339 --> 00:06:20.519
Is there something about me?

00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:21.820
Should I be worried about this?

00:06:21.820 --> 00:06:26.380
This is a trap you can fall into by spending too much time with your own data.

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:28.179
Should I worry about this?

00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:30.619
Well, let's look at the version.

00:06:30.619 --> 00:06:36.980
So the vertical green bars show the major versions of the watch OS software, and you

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:41.260
see that basically what's happening is between version six and version seven, they changed

00:06:41.260 --> 00:06:42.260
the measurement.

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:47.420
So what happened with version seven, they added sleep tracking.

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:51.380
So before version seven, when they were saying resting heart rate, what they were usually

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:56.220
ending up with was my heart rate at three in the morning or when I was asleep, near

00:06:56.220 --> 00:07:01.260
the lowest heart rate of the day, and they basically redefined the measure, let's say

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:07.220
improved the measure, so that it was only while you were awake.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:09.619
You have to watch out for this thing with any data set.

00:07:09.619 --> 00:07:13.839
You definitely have to watch out for it with the Apple health export.

00:07:13.839 --> 00:07:18.059
Sometimes there are clues to things like this, but sometimes there are not.

00:07:18.059 --> 00:07:20.820
Sometimes it's a black box, and you've got to figure this out on your own.

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:24.459
I'm going to show one more example because I like it a lot.

00:07:24.459 --> 00:07:27.579
This is a measure I'm very interested in, VO2 max.

00:07:27.579 --> 00:07:32.899
This is a measure of your aerobic fitness.

00:07:32.899 --> 00:07:39.380
When it's done directly, you're in a lab and they're measuring your exhaled gases and seeing

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:41.140
how well you're using oxygen.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:42.839
Obviously you don't do that with an iPhone.

00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:50.100
So they have an algorithm that estimates your VO2 max based on while you're walking a certain

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:55.059
distance, you're looking at your heart rate and the speed that you're traveling the distance.

00:07:55.059 --> 00:07:56.100
I look at this chart.

00:07:56.100 --> 00:08:00.859
I'm actually pretty good at inventing explanations for things that don't have explanations, but

00:08:00.859 --> 00:08:08.019
I look at this chart and I can't see anything, but if we add in the version numbers, we see

00:08:08.019 --> 00:08:14.260
that Apple is working on improving their measures, or I assume that's what's going on.

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:22.059
You see that between version five and version six, it goes up, then it goes back down.

00:08:22.059 --> 00:08:26.739
What's been happening more recently is less clear to me what's going on with versions.

00:08:26.739 --> 00:08:29.260
Maybe stuff is, maybe it isn't.

00:08:29.260 --> 00:08:30.260
I don't know.

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:32.700
You just have to look at the data and see.

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:38.099
I would love to know what my long-term trend is for this, to watch this over time, but

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:45.539
I look at this and certainly for the earlier years, no, there's nothing I can do with that.

00:08:45.539 --> 00:08:53.619
For all of these measures, you can dive in and get into stories like this.

00:08:53.619 --> 00:08:58.299
Let's get into one last measure, which is different than all the others, which is the

00:08:58.299 --> 00:09:05.340
electrocardiogram, which was added with the Apple Watch 4.

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:11.539
This is different because it actually has FDA approval as an actual medical device,

00:09:11.539 --> 00:09:16.900
doing the electrocardiogram, and then also the software that evaluates whether it's showing

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:18.739
signs of atrial fibrillation.

00:09:18.739 --> 00:09:23.940
Atrial fibrillation is a problem with the electrical signal in the upper chamber of

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:25.580
the heart.

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:32.739
I should emphasize for this population that it's generally a problem among the elderly,

00:09:32.739 --> 00:09:38.179
not a problem for the age demographic that is typical of this conference.

00:09:38.179 --> 00:09:43.099
You actually do the electrocardiogram by putting your finger on the stem of the watch, as is

00:09:43.099 --> 00:09:49.059
shown in the picture here, and then to the right, we have an actual little example of

00:09:49.059 --> 00:09:51.940
the electrocardiogram strip that it produces.

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:55.619
That strip is my strip, indicates atrial fibrillation.

00:09:55.619 --> 00:09:58.219
That was from October of 2020.

00:09:58.219 --> 00:10:04.859
That's the second time I had an episode of atrial fibrillation in seven years.

00:10:04.859 --> 00:10:09.700
I am elderly, so it's not so far-fetched.

00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:14.739
Got into the news recently because John Fetterman, the Senate candidate in Pennsylvania, was

00:10:14.739 --> 00:10:19.500
in atrial fibrillation, and it contributed to his stroke.

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:22.059
What do I do in a situation like this?

00:10:22.059 --> 00:10:24.419
Well, I do a Gigi plot.

00:10:24.739 --> 00:10:29.179
Again, when I had my episode of atrial fibrillation, I went to the emergency room.

00:10:29.179 --> 00:10:33.820
My doctor is not so surprised when I walk in with a Gigi plot.

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:38.260
I have a beautiful blood pressure plot.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:43.299
In the case of atrial fibrillation, I literally use the same function that I had written several

00:10:43.299 --> 00:10:46.380
years before for the first plot.

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:51.380
In this case, I have all the raw data from the atrial fibrillation episode, which actually

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:53.179
starts about 1230.

00:10:53.179 --> 00:10:55.739
What happened during the day was I was having a normal day.

00:10:55.739 --> 00:10:57.380
I went out for exercise in the morning.

00:10:57.380 --> 00:11:00.219
My heart rate slightly elevated, all perfectly normal.

00:11:00.219 --> 00:11:01.219
Sit down for lunch.

00:11:01.219 --> 00:11:07.419
Partway through lunch, I felt funny, checked, and realized something is going on.

00:11:07.419 --> 00:11:12.940
I have the raw data for the atrial fibrillation, but I don't have the expertise to do anything

00:11:12.940 --> 00:11:13.940
with that.

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.179
That's just beyond me.

00:11:16.179 --> 00:11:22.940
What I was able to do was to take the background heart rate information and to put the atrial

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:26.340
fibrillation episode in the context of the rest of the day.

00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:32.859
There is some slight relevance to when I was discussing this with the doctor.

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:38.940
What I could show was that within a minute or two after the episode started, there's

00:11:38.940 --> 00:11:42.500
an indication there that shows I was doing the electrocardiogram.

00:11:42.500 --> 00:11:43.500
I could tell.

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:46.619
This is evidence that I knew when I went into atrial fibrillation.

00:11:46.619 --> 00:11:52.820
Sometimes people don't know they're in atrial fibrillation, but I knew.

00:11:52.820 --> 00:11:58.619
You can also see that I came out of it before they hooked me up to an electrocardiogram

00:11:58.619 --> 00:12:00.659
in the emergency room.

00:12:00.659 --> 00:12:05.739
It actually goes on and off like throwing a light switch.

00:12:05.739 --> 00:12:11.179
None of these things I'm showing you have dramatic effects on my medical treatment.

00:12:11.179 --> 00:12:14.820
In this particular case, there was some slight advantage in having a discussion about whether

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:18.380
I needed to go in blood thinners and whatever.

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:22.900
The general point is that this stuff shows you a picture of your life.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:24.419
There's a lot of data there.

00:12:24.419 --> 00:12:29.979
If you have just looked at Palmer Penguins one too many times and you want to try something

00:12:29.979 --> 00:12:36.539
else with dplyr, you may have hundreds of thousands, millions of rows of data that you

00:12:36.539 --> 00:12:39.299
may find more interesting than Palmer Penguins.

00:12:39.299 --> 00:12:41.820
I've done a series of blog posts about this.

00:12:41.820 --> 00:12:46.299
If you have more interest in figuring out how to do this, there's a lot more information

00:12:46.299 --> 00:12:47.299
there.

00:12:47.299 --> 00:12:51.900
There's also a URL with an example of some other things that people have done with their

00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:52.900
data.

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:55.900
Thank you so much, John.

